= Chapter 2: Orbit Perturbations and Propagations

== Orbit Perturbations

For Keplerian orbits, the planet is assumed to be a point mass with no external forces acting. However for real spacecraft and satellites in orbit there exist disturbances which affect the motion of satellites in orbit. Though the central force from the body often dominates, some other perturbations include:

- Aerodynamic drag
- Solar radiation pressure
- Gravitational perturbations from a non-uniform, non-spherical central body
- Third body perturbations
- Electromagnetic drag
- Relativistic effects
- Yarkovsky-O'Keefe-Radzievskii-Paddack (YORP) effect from thermal radiation emission
- Outgassing, leaking and low thrust

A plot of the relative strength of these various disturbances for a LEO 2U CubeSat are shown in *@3-pertubations-1* and for a larger satellite in *@3-pertubations-2*.

